        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1982-11-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1982-11-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="181"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d181">
                <head>181. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_CWP_1">Clark</persName>) to Secretary of State
                        <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1">Shultz</persName> and the Representative to the
                    United Nations (<persName corresp="#p_KJJ_1">Kirkpatrick</persName>)<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d181fn1">Source: Department of State, Central Foreign
                        Policy File, P820166–2288. Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1982-11-09">November 9, 1982</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Law of the Sea Resolution at the <gloss target="#t_UN_1">UN</gloss>
                        General Assembly (U)</item>
                </list>
                <p>A draft resolution on Law of the Sea (<gloss target="#t_LOS_1">LOS</gloss>),
                    recently tabled at the <gloss target="#t_UN_1">UN</gloss> General Assembly,
                    contains objectionable provisions—including approval to finance the Preparatory
                    Commission under the <gloss target="#t_LOS_1">LOS</gloss> treaty out of the
                    regular <gloss target="#t_UN_1">UN</gloss> budget.<note n="2" xml:id="d181fn2"
                        >In telegram 3084 from New York, October 28, <gloss target="#t_USUN_1"
                            >USUN</gloss> outlined a draft resolution regarding the financing of the
                        Preparatory Commission. (Department of State, Central Foreign Policy File,
                        D820559–0648)</note> (U)</p>
                <p>Given the U.S. decisions not to sign the treaty and not to participate in the
                    Preparatory Commission, because of a number of unacceptable elements in the
                    seabed part, it is important that every effort be made in New York and in
                    appropriate capitals to change or defeat that part of the resolution in a way
                    that would not include any U.S. contributions <pb facs="0566" n="520"
                        xml:id="pg_520"/> to financing the Preparatory Commission. Efforts should
                    also be made to change or defeat other objectionable aspects. (C)</p>
                <p>Your review of the options available to the United States, in the event the
                    resolution passes with provision for financing the Preparatory Commission out of
                    the regular <gloss target="#t_UN_1">UN</gloss> budget, would be appreciated at
                    the earliest possible date. (C)</p>
                <p>FOR THE PRESIDENT:</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CWP_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">William P. Clark</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="3" xml:id="d181fn3">
                            <persName corresp="#p_CWP_1">Clark</persName> signed <persName
                                corresp="#p_CWP_1">Bill Clark</persName> above his typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
